SIMPLE: incursion
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Incursion
<hw>In*cur"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>incursio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>incursion</ets>. See
<er>Incur</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A running into; hence, an entering into a territory
with hostile intention; a temporary invasion; a predatory or harassing
inroad; a raid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Scythian, whose <qex>incursions</qex> wild⟦br⟧
Have wasted Sogdiana.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>incursions</qex> of the Goths disordered the affairs of
the Roman Empire.</q> <rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Attack; occurrence.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sins of daily <qex>incursion</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Invasion; inroad; raid; foray; sally; attack;
onset; irruption. See <er>Invasion</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incursive</ent>⟦br⟧
